title: Appointments to the Health and Medical Development Advisory Committee
content_text: p> The Government today (January 28) announced the re-appointment of Mr Ronald Arculli as Vice-Chairman of the Health and Medical Development Advisory Committee (HMDAC) for a term of two years with effect from March 1, 2011. At the same time, five serving non-official members of the committee have been re-appointed and 13 new non-official members have been appointed, for a term of two years. Dr Susan Fan Yun-sun The Secretary for Food and Health and the Chairman of the committee, Dr York Chow, welcomed the new members. He also thanked the outgoing members, namely Dr Margaret Chung Wai-ling, Dr David Fang, Professor Dennis Lam Shun-chiu,

Dr Jacqueline Lui Chiu-tong, Dr Louis Shih Tai-cho, Professor Grace Tang Wai-king, 
    Professor Thomas Wong Kwok-shing and Dr Loretta Yam Yin-chun, who have 
    served for six years, for their valuable advice and contribution to the 
    committee. They will retire from the committee with effect from March 1, 
    2011. A spokesman for the Food and Health Bureau said: "Following the completion 
    of the second stage public consultation on healthcare reform on January 7,

of the second stage public consultation on healthcare reform on January 7, 
    we are collating and analysing the views collected. The Government will 
    carefully consider how to address the views received from members of the 
    public and different organisations. Continued steer and support from the 
    HMDAC is essential to map out the way forward for the reform. "Given the important role of HMDAC in setting strategic direction for 
    development and financing of health and medical services in Hong Kong, we

would like to invite more professionals and representatives from different sectors so as to broaden the advisory base of the committee for the service reform implementation." The HMDAC is tasked to review and develop the service model for healthcare in both the public and private sectors, and propose long-term healthcare financing options.
